<h1>5.7 Order of numeral and noun</h1>
<h2 id="relevant-postag-codes">Relevant postag codes</h2>
<p>See <a href="https://papygreek.com/grammar/41">2.6. Numerals</a>.</p>
<h2 id="summary">Summary</h2>
<p>In non-articular NPs, the usual position of both cardinal and ordinal
numerals is postnominal. In articular NPs, however, they are found more
often in the internal position, i.e.&nbsp;between the article and the head.
The numeral can sometimes be found preposed in non-articular phrases for
the purpose of emphasis.</p>
<h2 id="examples-from-papygreeks-corpus">Examples from PapyGreek’s
corpus</h2>
<h3 id="cardinal-numerals">Cardinal numerals:</h3>
<ol type="1">
<li><p>φέρει δὲ καὶ Πατροκος ὄρνιθας ἀγρίους <strong>δύο</strong>, ὠιὰ
χήνεα <strong>ϛ</strong>.<br>
phérei dè kaì Patrokos órnithas agríous <strong>dúo</strong>, ōià khḗnea
<strong>ϛ</strong>.<br>
Patroklos is also bringing you two wild fowl and six goose’s eggs.
(transl. C.C. Edgar) <a href="https://papygreek.com/text/24058">p.cair.zen.2.59130</a>, l.
24-26, sent. 9.</p></li>
<li><p>αἱ <strong>τριάκοντα</strong> ἄρουραι αἱ περὶ Νῶιν βεβρεγμέναι
εἰσί·<br>
<a href="https://papygreek.com/text/1087">bgu.16.2665</a>, l. 15-16,
sent. 9.</p></li>
</ol>
<h3 id="ordinal-numerals">Ordinal numerals:</h3>
<ol start="3" type="1">
<li><p>Διονυσίωι τῶν φίλων καὶ στρατηγῶι παρὰ Ἁρμάιος τῶν ἐν τῶι μεγάλωι
Σαραπιείωι ὄντων ἐν κατοχῆι ἔτος <strong>πέμπτον</strong>, διαζῶντος δὲ
καὶ ἀφʼ ὧν ἐπαιτῶ ἐν τῶι ἱερῶι.<br>
<a href="https://papygreek.com/text/55763">upz.1.2</a>, l. 1-4, sent.
1</p></li>
<li><p>καὶ εἰ ἐκ τῶν <strong>πρώτων</strong> πυρῶν ἐμβάλῃ εἰς
Ἀλεξάνδρειαν , σήμανον·<br>
<a href="https://papygreek.com/text/1033">bgu.16.2611</a>, l. 4-5, sent.
4</p></li>
</ol>
<h2 id="discussion">Discussion</h2>
<p>The overwhelmingly predominant postnominal position of numerals in
non-articular phrases found in papyri is in contrast with the results
observed in the treebanked corpus of literary Greek, where the numeral
is found more commonly before the governing noun, regardless of whether
the noun is definite or not.</p>
<p>Preposing the numeral in non-articular NPs is often done in order to
achieve emphasis (also resulting in hyperbaton):</p>
<ol start="5" type="1">
<li>ἰδοῦ δὴ <strong>τρίτην</strong> ἐπιστολὴν σοι γράφω.<br>
idoû dḕ trítēn epistolḕn soi gráfō.<br>
<em>Look now, this is the third letter I am writing you.</em><br>
<a href="https://new.papygreek.com/text/1723">BGU.3.827</a>, l. 20-21,
sent. 7.</li>
<li><strong>τρίτον</strong> σοι τοῦτο, ἄδελφε, ὄστρακον γράφω.<br>
tríton soi toûto, ádelphe, óstrakon gráphō.<br>
<em>This is the third ostrakon, brother, that I write to you.</em><br>
<a href="https://papygreek.com/text/10186">o.claud.1.145</a>, l. 3-4,
sent. 2.</li>
</ol>
<p>In our corpus, numerals appear most commonly in dates (modifying
year, month, or day), prices and sums (e.g.&nbsp;δραχμή) and with words
signifying measures for land, produce etc. (e.g.&nbsp;ἀρτάβη, πῆχυς, χοῦς
etc.). The high number of instances of such phrases are mostly due to
the nature of our documents - letters, contracts, petitions, and other
texts concerning business affairs and employing widely used dating
formulae.</p>
<p>In the Duke-nlp corpus, the wide-spread tendency for placing the
numeral after the noun in non-articular phrases is also observable.</p>